RVV benchmark SpacemiT A100 (SpacemiT K3)

The SpacemiT-A100 is a 2-issue in-order RVA23 compatible core (actually, this isn't 100% confirmed yet, it may be missing the H extension), with a VLEN of 1024, running at 2.1GHz in the SpacemiT K3 SOC.
It is aimed at number-crunching applications and has support for the optional RVA23 extensions Zbc, Zbkc, Zcd, Zfbfmin, Zfh, Zvbc, Zvfbfwma, Zvfh, Zvkng, Zvknha, Zvksc, Zvksg, as well as a custom low-precision matrix extension.

  • Return to parent page

Based on this commit.

Thanks to Bruce Hoult, who had early access to the hardware, for running the benchmarks.

Benchmarks

  • memcpy
  • memset
  • memreverse
  • strlen
  • utf8 count
  • merge escaped lines
  • mandelbrot
  • reverse byte order of 32 bit elements
  • 4-bit lookup table
  • 6-bit lookup table
  • histogram
  • ascii to utf16 (zero extend 1->2 bytes)
  • ascii to utf32 (zero extend 1->4 bytes)
  • chacha20
  • poly1305
  • base64 encode
  • 8x8 transpose SEW=8
  • 8x8 transpose SEW=16
  • uarch measurement tool

Microarchitecture

SpacemiT published a paper covering the microarchitectural design of the SpacemiT K3: k3.pdf

The A100, seems to be based on the SpacemiT X60 design, upgraded to RVA23 and with a new VLEN=1024 vector unit.

"The A100 Vector Unit is driven by two parallel vector pipelines that perform vector-instruction splitting, dependency handling, and vector register-file reads/writes, with results produced primarily in stages VE3â€“VE5."

Instruction timings

The following are measured cycle averages when unrolling and looping over the given instruction, which should estimate the instruction throughput. The registers involved are randomized to usual values, that is floating point values are real numbers and not NaN/Inf, and instructions like vslide* stay within the vl range. Some valid vtype-instruction combinations are missing.

Example measurement code for vadd.vx
LMUL=1LMUL=4
bench_vaddvx_m1:
m_nop
	li a0, WARMUP
1:
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v9,v17,t1
	vadd.vx v10,v18,t2
	vadd.vx v11,v19,t3
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v13,v21,t5
	vadd.vx v14,v22,t6
	vadd.vx v15,v23,t7
	addi a0, a0, -1
	bnez a0, 1b
	li a0, LOOP
	rdcycle a1
1:
.rept UNROLL
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v9,v17,t1
	vadd.vx v10,v18,t2
	vadd.vx v11,v19,t3
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v13,v21,t5
	vadd.vx v14,v22,t6
	vadd.vx v15,v23,t7
.endr
	addi a0, a0, -1
	bnez a0, 1b
	fence.i
	rdcycle a0
	sub a0, a0, a1
	ret

bench_vaddvx_m4:
	m_nop
	li a0, WARMUP
1:
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	addi a0, a0, -1
	bnez a0, 1b
	li a0, LOOP
	rdcycle a1
1:
.rept UNROLL
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
	vadd.vx v8,v16,t0
	vadd.vx v12,v20,t4
.endr
	addi a0, a0, -1
	bnez a0, 1b
	fence.i
	rdcycle a0
	sub a0, a0, a1
	ret

Note: FP16 and some of the supported crypto instructions weren't recorded.
